Building a Feature Section with Flexbox Utility Classes
Tutorial

Building a Feature Section with Flexbox Utility Classes

6 steps

In this tutorial, you will learn how to use some of the Flexbox utility classes. Flexbox is a core CSS property to lay elements out in web development. Flexbox is useful at providing a more efficient way to lay out, align and distribute space among items in a container, even when their size is unknown or dynamic.

Additionally, you will learn the utility classes from the last property of the CSS Box Model: border and the trendy border-radius property. Secondly, you will see how you can style box shadows in Tailwind CSS.

The CSS pseudo-class “:hover” is essential in every webpage. The utility class for this pseudo-class is called a modifier in Tailwind CSS and allows you to apply any other utility class conditionally on this hover state.

Finally, to get your hands dirty, you will build a Feature Section that is often used in landing pages around the internet. To build this component you will use Flexbox, borders and hover states and possibly some utility classes that you learnt in this campaign.
Join us on Discord

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  1. Use borders and box-shadow utility classes
  2. Explain how the hover modifier works in Tailwind CSS
  3. Build a simple web page with flexbox utility classes

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Borders, Rounded Corners and Shadows

    In the previous tutorial, you learnt the spacing properties of the box model: margin and padding. In this step, you will learn to use the properties of borders which is the layer that outlines all the boxes of the elements. With these utility classes, you can change your border color, size, style and border radius. In particular, you will find giving your borders a more rounded look is very trendy in user interfaces. Watch the video above to learn to use these utility classes.

    Sometimes designs need more visual depth to increase the contrast between elements, to achieve this, developers use the CSS box-shadow property. In Tailwind CSS you can quickly set a suitable size and colors for shadows with its utility classes. In the two articles below, read the “Quick Reference” section to view all the available utility classes for this property and the “Basic Usage” section to learn how they work. In the first article, you'll learn how to set the shadow to be inside or outside the object and the size of the shadow. In the second article, you'll learn how to set colored shadows.

    🔗 Box Shadow

    🔗Box Shadow Color

  • Step 2: Handling Hover State

    Changing an element's properties when the element is hovered over helps in accessibility in certain cases. This CSS pseudo-class is a core property in web development and Tailwind CSS handles the hover state as a modifier. The hover modifier allows you to apply the hover state on any utility class to an element. To understand how this works check out the video above.

  • Step 3: Flexible Layouts with Flexbox Utility Classes

    Flexbox provides an efficient way to lay out, align and distribute space among items within a flex container, even when their size is unknown. You will use Flexbox mainly on small-scale layouts since it works just in one dimension. Using its utility classes will be easy if you understand how Flexbox works. In the video above, you will see how to use Flexbox properties utility classes, such as flex-direction, align-items and justify-content.

    Learn about Flexbox in our other tutorial.

  • Step 4: Let's Build! Preparing Your Project Folder

    We will now build a project using the utility classes that you just learnt. First, open your code editor (our preferred choice is Visual Studio Code) and create a folder called FeatureSection which will be the main folder of your project.

    In this folder, create 2 subfolders: dist and src. Next, create 2 files in the src folder: index.html and input.css.

    With the project folders and files created, let's install Tailwind CSS in the project. Open up the terminal and make sure that you are in the project's root directory, that is, FeatureSection and enter the following command.

    npm -y init

    Your terminal will prompt that a package.json file has been created in your root directory.

    Now, you will install the tailwind CLI tool as a devDependency, which means that the Tailwind CLI tool is a package only required during the development. Enter the following command in your terminal.

    npm install -D tailwindcss

    Your terminal will load the installation of the packages. After that, open your package.json file and check that 'tailwindcss' appears as a devDependency, which you should find in lines 12 and 13.

    Now that the Tailwind CLI tool is installed, we can run it by entering the following command in your terminal.

    npx tailwindcss init

    Notice that the tailwind.config.js file has been created in FeatureSection.

    In your tailwind.config.js file, update the “content” property in line 3 with the following code:

    content: ["./src/**/*.{html,js}"],
    JavaScript

    Finally, enter the following code in the input.css file. 

    @tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
    Plain text

    In the index.html file, add the code found in 'working code' below. You will notice that some utility classes that you learnt in the previous tutorials are being used. For example, the sizing utility classes w-1/2 to set the <header> and <main> to 50% of the <body>, and w-8 and h-8 to size the <svg> elements correctly. Spacing utility classes like mx-auto to center the <header> and <main> in the <body> and lastly some text styling and backgrounds utility classes such as text-lg, text-lime-500, font-semibold and bg-sky-100.

    Next, you need to build the utility classes using the Tailwind CLI Tool. Open your terminal and enter the following command.

    npx tailwindcss -i ./src/input.css -o ./dist/output.css --watch

    Your terminal will now rebuild only the utility classes used in your code every time you save new changes. Therefore, leave your terminal open during your development.

    With that, when you open the index.html file in your browser it should look like the image below.

  • Step 5: Building Time! Feature Section Component in Tailwind CSS

    It’s time to build a Feature Section component to test your skills using the utility classes learned in this tutorial. You will need to add the borders, rounded corners and hover states to this Feature Section component. You will also lay the cards and containers out using the Flexbox utility classes.

    Your finished project should look as close as possible to the video above. To achieve this, notice that all the colors are from the Tailwind Color Palette. You may also refer to the 'expected output' for a static representation of the component.

    Here are some pointers for you to note when completing your project:

    • In the header, the horizontal rule is the same colour as the heading text
    • All three cards have the same rounded border
    • In each card, the image and title are on the same line
    • All four buttons have the same border width
    • For the buttons in the cards, the border colour, background colour in hover state, shadow colour in hover state are the same 
  • Step 6: Checking Your Work

    You've worked hard on your feature section and it's time to check your code. Head over to our GitHub to view our index.html file.
